(4) Alignment of degree programs with high-demand or priority occupations as
identified by the state.
(5) Additional indicators determined by the Bd. of Regents to be relevant to career
alignment and economic development.
Proposed law requires the Bd. of Regents to ensure the dashboard is updated on a regular
basis, use consistent and clearly defined metrics, and present information in a manner that
is accessible and understandable to the general public.
Proposed law provides that nothing in proposed law will be construed to require the
disclosure of personally identifiable information, create performance funding requirements
or mandates for postsecondary institutions, or limit institutional autonomy over curriculum
or academic programming.
Proposed law allows the Bd. of Regents to adopt rules and enter into data-sharing
agreements as necessary to implement proposed law.
Present law (R.S. 17:3138.13) provides that Louisiana Works must perform an annual return
on investment analysis for the purpose of evaluating the relationship between industry-based
credentials earned by high school students and the students' attainment of high-wage, high-
demand jobs that are aligned with state workforce priorities.
Proposed law retains present law and further provides that the Bd. of Regents and Louisiana
Works must develop procedures to collect and analyze data on work-based learning
experiences such as internships, cooperative education programs, apprenticeships, or other
similar forms of work-based learning.
Proposed law provides that the data collected and analyzed may include information such
as whether the experience is paid or unpaid, the duration of the placement, and whether the
placement is part of a registered or credential-aligned program.
Proposed law provides that any procedures developed must ensure the collection and
analysis of data necessary to encourage and capture any work-based learning credits an
individual may have earned and the appropriate manner in which such credits may be
awarded.
Effective August 1, 2026.
(Adds R.S. 17:3138.2 and 3138.13(C))
